REASONS FOR JUDGMENT

SIMPSON J:

On 5 September 2025, I delivered reasons for judgment in relation to final parenting, property, and child support matters as between Ms Sum (“the applicant”) and Mr Lam (“the respondent”) (Sum & Lam (No 2) [2025] FedCFamC1F 610).
On 3 October 2025, the applicant filed a Notice of Appeal (proceedings number NAA469/2025). The appeal proceedings have been listed for hearing before a Full Court of the Federal Circuit and Family Court of Australia (Division 1) Appellate Jurisdiction on 29 January 2026. The applicant filed an Amended Notice of Appeal and Summary of Argument on 13 January 2026.
The final orders under challenge on appeal are as follows:
PROPERTY

Payment from the wife to the husband
Within 90 days from the date of these orders, the wife shall pay to the husband the following sums:
(a) $795,172; and

(b) $2,250.
Default sale of the [Suburb M] property
In the event that the wife fails to comply with Order 24 herein, the parties shall do all acts and things to list for sale and sell the property at [L Street], [Suburb M], New South Wales and being the whole of the land in Folio Identifier [redacted] and registered in the name of the wife (“the [Suburb M] property”), as agreed and failing agreement, in accordance with the following conditions of sale:
(a) The parties are to appoint a real estate agent to act on the sale and if they are unable to agree on the real estate agent, the husband is to provide the names of three suitably qualified real estate agents and the wife is to select one within two business days of receipt of the husband’s list, failing which the husband is to select one, and thereafter the person selected is to be appointed the real estate agent to act on the sale of the [Suburb M] property;

(b) The parties are authorised to communicate with and receive information from the real estate agent;

(c) The parties are to instruct a conveyancer to act on the sale of the [Suburb M] property and if they are unable to agree, the husband is to nominate three suitably qualified conveyancers and the wife is to select one within two business days of receipt of the husband’s list, failing which the husband is to select one, and thereafter the person selected is to be retained as the conveyancer to act on the sale;

(d) The parties are authorised to communicate with and receive information from the conveyancer;

(e) The parties are to give such instructions as are necessary to the conveyancer to prepare a Contract of Sale and the Contract of Sale is to provide for the completion of the sale within 42 days after the date of the contract unless otherwise agreed by the parties in writing;

(f) The parties are to list the [Suburb M] property for sale by way of public auction through a licensed auctioneer and if the parties cannot agree on the auctioneer, the parties are to appoint the licenced auctioneer nominated by the real estate agent;

(g) A reserve price is to be fixed by agreement between the parties after consultation with the real estate agent and auctioneer, and failing agreement, within 14 days of the auctioneer being appointed or three days before the auction (whichever is the latest), the reserve price is to be determined by the real estate agent in consultation with the auctioneer;

(h) The parties are to instruct the auctioneer to nominate a date of sale which must be not more than two months after the auctioneer has been appointed;

(i) Upon the parties accepting an offer for the purchase of the [Suburb M] property, the parties must within seven days execute the Contract of Sale and all other documents necessary to complete the sale;

(j) The parties may attend the auction sale of the [Suburb M] property and if the reserve price of the [Suburb M] property is not reached, the parties or such of them as in attendance at the auction, may negotiate with the highest bidder or any other bidder present at the auction or any other interested party in an effort to sell the [Suburb M] property at a price not more than 5 per cent below the reserve price as determined pursuant to Order 25(g) herein;

(k) If the [Suburb M] property is not sold at the auction, or within 14 days after the date of the auction, a further auction of the [Suburb M] property is to be held within three months after the date of the first auction, and at three month intervals until the [Suburb M] property is sold and for this purpose the relevant provisions of this Order 25 will apply;

(l) The parties are to co-operate with respect to the sale of the [Suburb M] property, including but not limited to:

(i) Making the keys available to the real estate agent;

(ii) Allowing access to the [Suburb M] property at all reasonable times to prospective purchasers, valuers and licensed real estate agents as may have been appointed by the parties;

(iii) Doing or saying nothing to hinder or prevent a sale being effected;

(iv) Signing all documents in relation to the sale approved by the real estate agent, auctioneer and, or, conveyancer as the case may be; and

(v) Maintaining the [Suburb M] property in reasonable condition and repair having regard to its present condition and the state thereof, pending completion of the sale of the [Suburb M] property.

In the event that the wife fails to comply with Order 24 herein and simultaneously with the settlement of the sale of the [Suburb M] property as provided for by Order 25 herein, the wife do all acts and things and sign all documents necessary to cause the payment of the proceeds of sale to be paid, in the following order and priority:
(a) To pay all costs and expenses of the sale of the [Suburb M] property including legal costs and disbursements, agents' commission, valuer's fees, advertising and sale expenses;

(b) To pay all amounts necessary to discharge all outstanding rates, electricity or other service accounts in respect of any service provided to the [Suburb M] property outstanding as at the date of the completion of the sale of the [Suburb M] property;

(c) To reimburse the wife for all payments made by her, with the prior written agreement of the husband, in preparing the [Suburb M] property for sale;

(d) To reimburse the husband for all payments made by him, with the prior written agreement of the wife, in preparing the [Suburb M] property for sale;

(e) To pay the remaining proceeds of sale as follows:
(i) To the husband in such amount as to give effect to an overall 58 per cent adjustment of the net value of the assets, having regard to the balance of these orders, to be paid into the trust account of Pigdon Norgate Family Lawyers; and

(ii) Subject to Order 27 herein, the balance to the wife.

From the wife’s share of the sale proceeds pursuant to Order 26(e)(ii) herein, the amount of $2,250 is to be paid directly to the husband.
Pending the wife’s compliance with Order 24 herein or the sale of the [Suburb M] property pursuant to Order 25 herein, the parties each be restrained from charging or encumbering the [Suburb M] property or creating, or increasing any liability secured against the [Suburb M] property, without the prior written consent of the other party.
Joint NAB Account ending ..71
Within 14 days from the date of these orders, the parties do all things and sign all documents as necessary to pay the balance in the joint account as to 58 per cent to the husband and 42 per cent to the wife and thereafter close the joint account.
Pursuant to those orders, the order relating to the default sale of the Suburb M property ought to have come into effect on 5 December 2025 (when the payments to the respondent from the applicant had not been paid). From the date of judgment delivery, the applicant was provided 90 days to make two payments to the respondent, failing which, the orders provide for the process by which the parties are to sell the Suburb M property and for the respondent to receive the two payments, being:
(a) An amount such that the respondent receives 58 per cent of the total net pool, as was found by me as being just and equitable; and

(b) The amount of $2,250 to be paid by the applicant to the respondent without adjustment for the reimbursement of the applicant’s half share of an expert report.

(collectively referred to as “the outstanding payments”)
On 9 December 2025, the applicant filed an affidavit and an Application in a Proceeding in which she sought to stay Orders 24 to 29 of the final orders made by me on 5 September 2025, pending the outcome of the appeal (those are the orders the subject of her appeal). As the above summary makes clear, the applicant did not file her Application in a Proceeding until the time for payment under Order 24 had passed.
Following the applicant’s filing of her Application in a Proceeding, I listed the matter for Case Management Hearing on 12 December 2025, at which I adjourned the matter to 16 January 2026 for interim hearing, accommodating the preferences of the applicant for a later hearing date.
In the interim, and as ordered, the respondent filed an affidavit and a Response to Application in a Proceeding on 19 December 2025. In that Response, the respondent agreed to stay Orders 24(a), 25, 26, 27 and 28, on the following terms:
2. In the event that the Wife’s Appeal is unsuccessful:
Interest on the sums payable to the Husband pursuant to Order 24(a) and 24(b) of the Final Orders still owing as at 5 December 2025 shall attract interest payable at the rate prescribed under the Family Law Rules, from 5 December 2025 until paid;
The total sum payable pursuant to Orders 24(a) and 24(b) (if relevant) of the Final Orders shall be payable within seven (7) days of final determination of the appeal; and
In the event of the Wife’s default of Order 2(b) herein, then the default provisions pursuant to Orders 25 shall take effect; and
Order 27(e) of the Final Orders shall be varied to provide for the payment to give effect to an overall adjustment of 58% of the net value of the assets, together with the interest payable pursuant to Order 2(a) herein.
For clarity, in the event that the Wife’s Appeal is successful then the provisions of Order 2 shall not apply.
That the wife shall pay to the Husband the sum of $2,250 as reimbursement for the costs of the expert report, being the sum payable pursuant to Order 24(b) of the Final Orders.
The Wife shall take all steps to “unblock” the parties Joint Account within 24 hours of the date of these Orders, and thereafter the parties shall divide the proceeds in such proportions as set out in Paragraph 29 of the Final Orders.
Order 31 of the Final Orders shall be varied such that the Husband will attend the [Suburb M] property on 24 January 2026 at 10am to collect the personal property contained therein, and the purposes of this Order:
The Wife shall take all steps to ensure that the Husband can attend the property;
The Wife shall recompense the husband for the transportation costs/removalist within 7 days of being sent the invoice/receipt from the husband
The Wife is at liberty to remain at the property; and
Both parties shall keep a reasonable distance from each other while the Husband is collecting the belongings set out at Order 31 of the Final Orders.
The respondent in his case outline document indicates that his consent to the stay of Order 28 was expressed in error (that order restrains both parties from dealing with or encumbering the Suburb M property, save for compliance with the final orders).
Both parties sought that the other pay their costs relating to the competing proposals.
The applicant in her case outline document sought to defer consideration of the orders sought by the respondent to a date following the finalisation of her appeal and only if her appeal was unsuccessful. The basis for the deferral of consideration of the respondent’s relief in his Response to an Application in a Proceeding was not clear. In circumstances where the respondent filed his Response in accordance with the directions made on 12 December 2025, it remains open to the court to consider the relief sought in that document.
On the morning of 16 January 2026, the applicant communicated with Chambers to the effect that she was unwell and that she would be attending hospital for urgent review that day. Her communication, shared with the respondent’s lawyers, included a medical certificate. The parties agreed that the matter could be determined in chambers on the papers and the hearing was vacated on that basis.

DOCUMENTS RELIED UPON

By way of communication from Chambers, it was agreed that I would have regard to the following (save for 12(a)(vi) below, which I admitted having received no response on behalf of the respondent about such):
(a) The applicant relied upon:
(i) Her Application in a Proceeding filed 9 December 2025;

(ii) Her affidavit filed 9 December 2025;

(iii) Her case outline document filed 12 January 2025 (Exhibit 1);

(iv) A letter from a Case Manager at the NAB to the applicant dated 14 January 2026 (Exhibit 2);

(v) An email sent from the applicant to the Court on 16 January 2026 (Exhibit 3); and

(vi) An email sent by the applicant to the respondent dated 7 October 2025 (Exhibit 7).

(b) The respondent relied upon:

(i) His Response to Application in a Proceeding filed 19 December 2025;

(ii) His affidavit filed 19 December 2025;

(iii) His case outline document filed 14 January 2026 (Exhibit 4);

(iv) Annexure “A” to the respondent’s affidavit being a AQ Bank Statement (Exhibit 5); and

(v) Annexure “B” to the respondent’s affidavit being bank account statements from 4 September 2025 to 18 December 2025 for a NAB account (Exhibit 6).

ISSUES IN DISPUTE

In circumstances where the respondent agreed to the stay of some of the final orders on terms, the ambit of the dispute was narrow:
(a) Whether Orders 24(a), 25, 26, and 27 should be stayed on the terms as proposed by the respondent, including:
(i) Should interest be payable to the respondent upon the outstanding payments, in the event the appeal does not succeed;

(ii) Whether the payment required by the applicant under Order 24(b) should be treated separately from the default provisions provided in Orders 25 to 27 inclusive or whether Order 24(b) should be stayed as sought by the applicant; and, or

(iii) Whether Order 29 be stayed as sought by the applicant.

(b) What order, if any, should be made to address the failure of the parties to comply with Order 31, to enable the respondent to collect his personal belongings from the Suburb M property and noting that Order is not the subject of the appeal and its operation is not the subject of the stay application.

(c) Whether Order 28 is to be stayed pending the outcome of the appeal.

THE LAW

I respectfully refer to and adopt the summary by Schonell J in Kaplan & Hankel (No 2) [2025] FedCFamC1F 210, as to the principles relevant to the consideration of a stay, pending an appeal in financial matters:
The Court’s power to grant a stay pending an appeal is discretionary and is embodied in part in r 13.12(2) of the Federal Circuit and Family Court of Australia (Family Law) Rules 2021 (Cth) (“the Rules”).
A stay is not ordered as a matter of right. The power to order a stay is incidental to the right of appeal.
In order to justify a stay, the party seeking the stay bears the onus to establish that the circumstances warrant a departure from the general rule that a judgment is presumed to be correct and liable to be enforced (Alexander v Cambridge Credit Corporation Ltd (Receivers appointed) (1985) 2 NSWLR 685 at 693–694) and a court should not deprive a successful litigant of the fruits of litigation without just cause (Kelly and Kelly [1980] FamCA 88; (1981) FLC 91-007).
The principles applicable to a stay in financial proceedings are well settled and are conveniently set out by the Full Court in Aldridge & Keaton (Stay Appeal) [2009] FamCAFC 106 which records as follows:
The principles to be applied in determining an application for a stay of orders both in the general law and in respect of parenting proceedings are also well known (see The Commissioner of Taxation of the Commonwealth of Australia v Myer Emporium Limited [No.1] [1986] HCA 13; (1986) 160 CLR 220 at 222; Alexander v Cambridge Credit Corporation (1985) 2 NSW LR 685; Jennings Construction Limited v Burgundy Royale Investments Pty Limited [1986] HCA 84; (1986) 161 CLR 681; Clemett & Clemett [1980] FamCA 90; (1981) FLC 91-013; JRN & KEN v IEG & BLG [1998] HCATrans 263; (1998) 72 ALJR 1329 at 1332). The authorities stress the discretionary nature of the application which should be determined on its merits. Principles relevant to this matter include the following:
the onus to establish a proper basis for the stay is on the applicant for the stay. However it is not necessary for the applicant to demonstrate any “special” or “exceptional” circumstances;
a person who has obtained a judgment is entitled to the benefit of that judgment;
a person who has obtained a judgment is entitled to presume the judgment is correct;
the mere filing of an appeal is insufficient to grant a stay;
the bona fides of the applicant;
a stay may be granted on terms that are fair to all parties - this may involve a court weighing the balance of convenience and the competing rights of the parties;
a weighing of the risk that an appeal may be rendered nugatory if a stay is not granted – this will be a substantial factor in determining whether it will be appropriate to grant a stay;
some preliminary assessment of the strength of the proposed appeal – whether the appellant has an arguable case.
There are other relevant considerations which include whether the stay has been brought promptly and is not merely a delaying tactic as well as the period of time during which the stay will be in place.
The appeal is listed for hearing on 29 January 2026, a date less than two weeks from the date on which the Application in a Proceeding was listed to be heard.

CONSIDERATION

The respondent has approached the Application in a Proceeding pragmatically, and has proposed terms, upon which certain of the final orders the subject of the pending appeal might be stayed by agreement. The primary term sought by the respondent is to make express, by way of order, the requirement that the applicant pay interest on the outstanding payments due under the final orders, at the rate specified in the Federal Circuit and Family Court of Australia (Family Law) Rules 2021 (Cth) (“the Rules”). This approach ensures that the applicant will not be compelled to take steps to sell the Suburb M property, pending the conclusion of the appeal.
Section 117B of the Family Law Act 1975 (Cth) (“the Act”) sets out the framework for payment of interest upon moneys ordered to be paid, on the following terms:
117B Interest on moneys ordered to be paid
(1) Subject to any order made by the court under subsection (2), where, in proceedings under this Act, a court makes an order for the payment of money (other than an order for the payment by way of maintenance of a periodic sum), interest is payable, at the rate prescribed by the applicable Rules of Court, from:
(a) the date on which the order is made; or

(b) the date on which the order takes effect;

whichever is later, on so much of the money as is from time to time unpaid.
(2) A court that makes an order for the payment of money as mentioned in subsection (1) may order that interest is not payable on the money payable under the first‑mentioned order or may order:
(a) that interest is payable at a rate specified in the order, being a rate other than the rate prescribed by the applicable Rules of Court; or

(b) that interest is payable from a date specified in the order, being a date other than the date from which the interest would be payable under subsection (1).

In circumstances where Order 24 required the payment of two sums of money by the applicant to the respondent 90 days after the orders were made, the respondent is entitled to interest on the unpaid money, subject to the outcome of the hearing of the appeal. Rule 10.17 of the Rules sets out the prescribed rate of interest as follows:
The prescribed rate at which interest is payable under paragraphs 87(11)(b), 90KA(b), 90UN(b) and subsection 117B(1) of the Family Law Act is:
(a) in respect of the period from 1 January to 30 June in any year—the rate that is 6% above the cash rate last published by the Reserve Bank of Australia before that period commenced; and

(b) in respect of the period from 1 July to 31 December in any year—the rate that is 6% above the cash rate last published by the Reserve Bank of Australia before that period commenced.

Note: For the date from which interest is payable, see paragraphs 87(11)(b), 90KA(b) and subsection 117B(1) of the Family Law Act.
The respondent has sought that such an order be expressed as coming into effect only in circumstances where the applicant’s appeal is dismissed by the Full Court. To avoid (hopefully) the necessity of further court events, the respondent seeks to make express the legislative obligation to pay interest on outstanding sums, as ordered. That is a reasonable request in the circumstances of this case, particularly when the applicant remains self-represented.
The respondent is entitled to assume that the final orders are correct until such time as the Full Court determines otherwise. More than four weeks have now passed since the applicant has failed to pay the ordered sums to the respondent and there can be no argument that he has been denied some of the “fruits of his judgment” (noting the other property the respondent held and retained under the final orders).
Under Order 25 of the final orders, and with the applicant having failed to make the ordered payments, the parties are at liberty to take steps to sell the Suburb M property. Failing agreement being reached between them, the applicant belatedly filed this application to secure the court’s assistance in avoiding that outcome. The respondent agrees to stay the operation of that order on the terms summarised above. The applicant seeks to retain that property and the respondent’s agreement to stay the default sale order of the Suburb M property means that may remain possible, subject to the outcome of the appeal.
The applicant brought her appeal in a timely fashion and has taken steps to prosecute that appeal, save for seeking certain time extensions to account for her recent ill health. However, this Application in a Proceeding was filed after the date on which the payments under the final orders were due, though the affidavits make clear certain discussions occurred about these matters prior to the application being filed.
The applicant does not make clear in her Amended Notice of Appeal or her Summary of Argument, the outcome which she says should be achieved, in the event the appeal succeeds. That absence of particularity means that more specific terms for the operation of the stay could not be sought (for example, identifying a lesser payment to be made to the respondent, if the applicant was to be successful in her appeal).
As a consequence of the concessions made by the respondent, he will be denied any payment until the completion of the appeal, at the earliest. The final orders provided that $795,172 and $2,250 was to be paid to the respondent by the applicant. He has not received any portion of those sums. The respondent deposes to his own financial pressures, as he awaits receipt of the outstanding payments, including that he has a debt to a litigation funder of around $435,000 and which is subject to interest at a rate of 9.4 per cent (Exhibit 5) and other fees. The respondent also deposes to mortgage liabilities over the properties he has retained under the final orders, of around $2,300,000.
The applicant submits that the respondent’s financial circumstances are superior to hers and that she will suffer hardship if interest (at the rate set under the Rules) was to apply to the outstanding payments. I am not persuaded by that argument. The respondent is entitled to presume that the orders are correct, and he is owed a total of $797,422 from the applicant under those orders. The applicant does not identify any lesser sum which she says would be payable to the respondent, in the event the appeal was to succeed (or her view of the correct outcome more generally in the event the appeal was to succeed).
The applicant wishes to retain the Suburb M property, which remains unencumbered and which is registered in her sole name, and she has had exclusive use and control of that property since the final orders were made. At the final hearing, that property had an agreed value of $3,600,000. The financial circumstances of both parties were assessed at the time of the final hearing, and those circumstances informed the final orders.
The respondent estimates that in the event the appeal did not succeed, and if the applicant does not have the resources available to make the outstanding payments, it may take another two to three months for the property to be sold. In the time awaiting the outstanding payments and, or, the sale of the Suburb M property, the respondent continues to be denied the use of the outstanding payment funds, to his financial detriment.
I will make the order sought by the respondent to make express the obligation on the applicant to pay interest, in accordance with the Rules, from the date the payments were due.
Additionally, the respondent sought to vary the time for payment of the sum of $2,250 due to him under the final orders and to require that payment immediately. That smaller payment forms part of the obligations under Order 24 of the final orders. The applicant does not address why this more modest sum has not been paid by her, noting this amount was to reimburse the respondent for valuation fees paid by him during the currency of the proceedings and the obligation arose some considerable time before the final hearing.
The applicant and respondent have funds held in a joint bank account which, under the final orders (Order 29), were to be divided between them in particular proportions. That order has not been complied with, and the respondent seeks an order that this occurs immediately.
Each party deposes to some unusual transactions made by the other using funds in that joint account following the making of the final orders.
The respondent deposes to taking necessary steps, after the final orders were made, to ensure that the joint account was no longer being used for purposes of his other property holdings. The respondent deposes to taking steps to instruct the bank in accordance with Order 29 but then being advised that the applicant had instructed the bank to “freeze” the account.
The explanation offered by the applicant about her failure to comply with Order 29 was somewhat confusing and on her own account, it appeared she took steps to direct the bank to suspend the account (consistent with the respondent’s evidence).
The account holds an amount of $16,048.53. I am not persuaded that it is necessary for the operation of Order 29 to be stayed until the conclusion of the applicant’s appeal. These funds can be divided between the parties at this time. The amount in question is very modest compared to the overall property pool, as found by me in Sum & Lam (No 2) [2025] FedCFamC1F 610, which was in excess of $7,750,171.
There is no principled reason why Order 29 should not be performed forthwith. If the Full Court allows the appeal, the fact of the division of that account may readily be considered in any future determination of the financial matter between the parties (whether on a re-exercise of discretion, as sought by the applicant, or on a re-hearing). I will make the order sought by the respondent about these funds.
In addition, to avoid further delay or uncertainty, I will order the applicant to pay to the respondent the outstanding sum of $2,250 upon the applicant gaining access to her share of the funds in the joint account (and will discharge the final orders relating to this payment as a consequence of these new orders).
The respondent proposes that the stay of the orders for payment and sale of the Suburb M property operate until the determination of the appeal. In the event the appeal is unsuccessful, the respondent proposes that the payment required under the final orders be due seven days after the determination of the appeal. The applicant submits that such a time frame is insufficient and in circumstances where she has been unwell, such a time frame is unreasonable and will cause her additional hardship.
The final orders allowed the applicant 90 days from the orders in which to make the outstanding payments. I infer from the applicant’s evidence that she has taken no steps to explore finance to make the required payments.
The respondent in the meantime has been denied access to these funds and has set out in his evidence the impact of that delay. I will allow the applicant some modest additional time (14 days from the dismissal of the appeal) in which to make the outstanding payment, failing which, the default orders for the sale of the Suburb M property will apply. I expect that the Full Court will determine the appeal promptly and in any event, the applicant has been on notice of her obligations since 5 September 2025. Despite that, it appears that she has taken no steps towards arranging a source of funds from which to make the outstanding payment to the respondent. It is not reasonable that the burden of the applicant’s inaction should continue to fall on the respondent.
The applicant also sought the stay of Order 28. There is no reason why that order should be stayed. It is entirely appropriate that pending the determination of the appeal and, or, the payments and, or, sale of the Suburb M property, that the parties should not charge, dispose of, or encumber the Suburb M property. That order will remain operable.
The difficulties relating to performance of Order 31 remain baffling. It is not clear on the evidence of the respondent why he did not take steps to obtain his personal property from the Suburb M property in the time frame envisaged in the orders. The respondent deposes to communications between the parties about that process from 15 September 2025. Exhibit 7 makes clear that on 7 October 2025, the applicant wrote to the respondent directing him to collect the items from the Suburb M property by 12 October 2025. The evidence does not make clear why collection did not occur on that day. Upon arriving at the home on 8 November 2025 to collect the items, the respondent deposes to then being obstructed by the applicant and being unable to access the home to remove his property. The affidavit of the respondent suggests that the applicant sought to apply conditions to that process outside the terms of the final orders and deemed the approach being undertaken that day by the respondent to be unacceptable to her.
I will accede to the orders sought by respondent about the collection of his property which shall occur on 24 January 2026. If the applicant wishes to be present at that time, that is a matter for her. The respondent is at liberty to secure the assistance of third parties in that process (noting that some of the items would require more than one person to move them).
The respondent also seeks an order that the applicant meet the costs of the removalist/transport he uses “to compensate for not complying” with his earlier attempt to remove the property. The respondent does not provide evidence as to the cost likely to be incurred by him and the evidence about the events leading to the November occasion when he attempted to collect his property is limited. I am not persuaded to make an order that the applicant meet the cost (whatever it may be) of the respondent’s removalist. This is particularly so in circumstances where it remains unclear why the parties did not seek to give effect to Order 31 in the timeframe required under the orders (which timeframe had been sought by the respondent at the final hearing).

The merits of the appeal

In circumstances where the respondent has effectively conceded the primary relief sought by the applicant, and a stay is being granted, I don’t propose to consider the merits of the appeal, save to make the following observations.
This is an appeal against a discretionary judgment and accordingly, the applicant will face the well-recognised challenges set out in House v The King [1936] 55 CLR 499.
The applicant contends (among other things) that incorrect findings of fact were made, inadequate reasons were provided, and the exercise of discretion was “plainly unreasonable” and wrong. There may be some challenges for the applicant in the hearing of the appeal given the manner in which the grounds of appeal are expressed and where certain contentions the applicant now makes are not consistent with the manner in which the final hearing was conducted on her behalf. I also note the very high bar which must be achieved to establish a miscarriage of justice arising from incompetent legal representation (TKWJ v The Queen [2002] HCA 46; (2002) 212 CLR 124; OP & TP & The Child Representative (Conduct of Counsel) [2002] FamCA 1155; (2002) 30 Fam LR 281; Bligh & Trott [2023] FedCFamC1A 95 at [12]).

Costs

Each party sought costs with respect to the stay proceedings. Leaving aside what costs the applicant would identify in circumstances where she is self-represented, I am not persuaded of any circumstances which would justify deviating from the general principle under s 114UB(1) – that each party should bear their own costs. This is particularly so where each of the parties has achieved certain of the outcomes they sought in these proceedings (neither party has been wholly unsuccessful, in accordance with s 114UB(3)(e) of the Act) and the matter was in any event, resolved by way of a hearing on the papers.
Consequently, there will be no order as to costs.
